                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 E.W./10–1444: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Greek Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-14T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 14, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 12:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Greek Series 365. The Greek Minister to Egypt<note n="6" xml:id="d388fn6"
                        >Dimitrios Pappas.</note> has notified me verbally that last Wednesday
                    afternoon his colleague in Moscow was summoned by Mr. Molotoff and informed that
                    Bulgarian troops have been ordered to evacuate Greek territory completely, the
                    movement to be completed in 15 days. Pappas added with evident relief and
                    satisfaction that the whole tone of Mr. Molotoff’s conversation with the Greek
                    representative was “more friendly and easy” than has been the case
                    previously.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Caserta as No. 96 and to Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
